# Cross-IDE Handoff Protocol

## Purpose

Enable any agent or IDE (Cursor, Codex, Antigravity, Xcode) to resume work started by another agent or IDE without loss of context, across multiple machines and environments.

## Machines & IDEs

| Machine | IDEs |
|---------|------|
| MacBook (black) | Cursor, Antigravity |
| MacBook (silver) | Cursor, Antigravity |
| Mac Mini | Codex, Antigravity, Xcode |

Branch naming encodes the machine+IDE identity: `dev/<machine><ide>` (e.g., `dev/minicodex`, `dev/blackcursor`).

## Handoff Document

When finishing a work session, write a handoff document to `docs/handoffs/`.

**Filename:** `YYYY-MM-DD-<branch>-<short-summary>.md`

**Template:**

```markdown
# Handoff: [Short Summary]

- **Date:** YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM (timezone)
- **Branch:** dev/<developer>
- **IDE/Agent:** [Cursor | Codex | Antigravity | Xcode]
- **Machine:** [MacBook black | MacBook silver | Mac Mini]

## What Was Done
- [Bullet list of completed work]

## What's Next
- [Bullet list of remaining tasks]

## Blockers
- [Any blockers or issues that need resolution]

## Assumptions Made
- [Decisions made without full information]

## Files Changed
- [List of key files modified]

## Branch State
- [ ] All changes committed
- [ ] Pushed to remote
- [ ] Tests passing
- [ ] No uncommitted work
```

## Before Starting Work

1. Check `docs/handoffs/` for the latest handoff on your branch or related branches.
2. Read it before starting to understand context.
3. Pull latest from the branch.

## Overnight Autonomous Work

When local LLM agents (via Ollama on Mac Mini) run overnight:
- They must write a handoff document when their session ends.
- Morning cloud-based agents read the handoff before continuing.
- The handoff must include branch state and any assumptions made.

## Future: LiNKbrain Integration

This file-based handoff system is temporary. When LiNKbrain is ready, handoffs will be persisted as structured memory entries with vector search, replacing the `docs/handoffs/` folder.
